<section xml:id="sec_solving-forces0" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Force Analysis</title>

<activity>
	<title>Warmup</title>
	<p>
		
	</p>
    <p>
		Observe the motion of the aircar in the video below.
	</p>

	<video youtube="3SVwxKqTkaY"><description>A demonstration of an aircart moving across a table.</description>
      </video>

	<p>
		Carry out the steps below for what you observed in the video.
	</p>

	<ol>
		<li>
			<p>
				Identify a system and choose a reference frame
			</p>
		</li>
		<li> 
			<p>
				Identify external forces and draw a free-body diagram.
			</p>
		</li>
		<li>
			<p>
				Identify the acceleration
			</p>
		</li>
		<li>
			<p>
				Use the Laws of Motion to make claims about the forces
			</p>
		</li>
		<li>
			<p>
				Check that your claims make sense
			</p>
		</li>
	</ol>
	</activity>

	<p>
		The five steps above make up a general strategy that can be used to approach many physical situations,  
		This strategy is typically known as the <q>Forces</q> approach to solving problems, or <term>Force Analysis</term>.
	</p>

	<hypothesis xml:id="force-analysis">
	<title>Force Analysis</title>
		<statement>
	<ol>
		<li>
			<p>
