<activity xml:id="class_groceries">
		<title>The Bag of Groceries</title>
		<p>
			
		</p>
		<p>
			Consider the three situations below.  For each, use <xref ref="force-analysis" text="title"/> to understand what is happening.
		</p>
		<ol marker="a">
			<li>
				<p>
					You hold a bag of groceries in your hand.
				</p>
			</li>
			<li>
				<p>
					You lower the bag of groceries; the bag moves downward faster and faster.
				</p>
			</li>
			<li>
				<p>
					You lift the bag of groceries; the bag moves upward at constant speed
				</p>
			</li>
		</ol>
	</activity>

	<activity xml:id="class_strange-box">
	<title>Moving a Strange Box</title>
<introduction>
<p></p>
    <p>
      Mike and Lucas are attempting to move a box, which does not move.
    </p>
	<figure xml:id="lom_StrangeBox">
		<title>Strange Box Figure</title>
	  <caption>Two people trying to move a box.</caption>
  <image source="StrangeBox.png" width = "60%">
		<description></description>
  </image>
</figure>
</introduction>
	
	<task>
	<p> 
		Use <xref ref="force-analysis" text="title"/> to understand what is happening:
	</p>
	
	<ol>
		<li>
			<p>
				Identify a system and choose a reference frame
			</p>
		</li>
		<li> 
			<p>
				Identify external forces and draw a free-body diagram
			</p>
		</li>
		<li>
			<p>
				Identify the acceleration
			</p>
		</li>
		<li>
			<p>
				Use the Laws of Motion to make claims about the forces
			</p>
		</li>
		<li>
			<p>
				Check that your claims make sense
			</p>
		</li>
	</ol>
	</task>
	<task>
	<p>
      El now pushes the box with a mental force, and it finally begins to speed up.
    </p>
		<figure xml:id="lom_StrangerBox">
			<title>Stranger Box Figure</title>
		  <caption>Three people trying to move a box.</caption>
      <image source="StrangerBox.png" width = "60%">
			<description></description>
			</image>
    </figure>

	<ol>
		<li>
			<p>
				Modify your free-body diagram
			</p>
		</li>
		<li> 
			<p>
				Indicate the direction of the acceleration
			</p>
		</li>
		<li>
			<p>
				Write a symbolic expression for the magnitude of the acceleration in terms of the other forces
			</p>
		</li>
	</ol>
	</task>
</activity>


<activity xml:id="class_deducing-forces">
	<title>Deducing Forces</title>
<introduction>
<p></p>
    <p>
      In each case below, three forces act on a <m>0.5 \mathrm{~kg}</m> object.  
	  Two of the forces are shown on the free-body diagrams, but the third is missing.
    </p>
		</introduction>
		<figure xml:id="lom_2Forces">
			<title>Three Cases Figure</title>
		  <caption>Three cases, each showing two of the three forces acting on an object.</caption>
      <image source="2Forces.png" width = "70%">
			<description></description>
			</image>
    </figure>
	<p>
		Draw and label the missing force vector for each case for the three motions below.
	</p>
	<ul>
		<li>
			<p>
				Motion 1: <m>a = 2 \mathrm{~m/s^2}</m> to the right
			</p>
		</li>
		<li> 
			<p>
				Motion 2: <m>a = 3 \mathrm{~m/s^2}</m> downward
			</p>
		</li>
		<li>
			<p>
				Motion 3: constant speed
			</p>
		</li>
	</ul>
</activity>


	<activity xml:id="class_book-on-ramp">
	<title>The Book on the Ramp</title>
<introduction>
<p></p>
    <p>
      A physics textbook is on a tilted, frictionless table, supported by a string.
    </p>
	<figure xml:id="lom_BookRamp">
		<title>Book on a Ramp Figure</title>
	  <caption>A book on a ramp connected to a string.</caption>
  <image source="BookRamp.png" width = "50%">
		<description></description>
		</image>
</figure>
		</introduction>
		
	<p>
		Use <xref ref="force-analysis" text="title"/> to describe the forces acting on the book.
	</p>
	<ol>
		<li>
			<p>
				Identify a system and choose a reference frame (what reference frame do you think will make approaching this situation easiest?)
			</p>
		</li>
		<li> 
			<p>
				Identify external forces and draw a free-body diagram
			</p>
		</li>
		<li>
			<p>
				Identify the acceleration
			</p>
		</li>
		<li>
			<p>
				Use the Laws of Motion to make claims about the forces (assume you know the magnitude of the gravitational force is <m>F^g</m>.)
			</p>
		</li>
		<li>
			<p>
				Check that your claims make sense (suppose the table is slanted so that it becomes steeper: 
				does the magnitude of each force increase, decrease, or stay the same?)
			</p>
		</li>
	</ol>
</activity>



